Let the trapezoid $ABCD$ have $AB$ as the longer base, $AB=16$. Let the inscribed circle have center $O$.  
Let the feet of the altitudes from $C$ and $D$ to $AB$ be $E$ and $F$, respectively.
Note that $\triangle CEA$ is similar to $\triangle DOF$, since $\angle CEA=90^{o}$ and $\angle DOF = \angle COA = 2\angle OCA = 2(\angle ACO + \angle ACO) = 4\angle OCA = 90^{o}-\angle CEA$. Moreover, $\frac{CA}{DE}=\frac{OA}{OF} = \frac{EO}{OD}$.
Since $[ABCD] = \frac{DE+CA}{2}(AB)$, we have  
\begin{align*}
\frac{[ABCD]}{DE+CA} &= \frac{\frac{AB}{2}(DE+CA)}{AB} \\
\frac{[ABCD]}{DE+CA} &= \frac{DE+CA}{2}
\end{align*}
Hence the area of trapezoid $ABCD$ equals half the harmonic mean of the bases $DE$ and $CA$.
Because of symmetry, note that $EO=OF=\frac{16}{2}-x=8-x$ and $OD=OB+x=x+6$, where $x=12\sin{y}$ and the base angle is $\angle DAB=y$; subbing in values, $EO=OD\implies 8-x = x+6\implies x=1$. Therefore $DE=6x=6$ and $CA=8x-32=8$;  
$\frac{[ABCD]}{DE+CA} = \frac{DE+CA}{2}\implies \frac{[ABCD]}{6+8} = \frac{6+8}{2}\implies [ABCD]=4\cdot7 = 28$. $<end think>$</think> <answer>19</answer>

